Anonymous Thu 16 Mar 2023 01:41:53 No.55090665 Report
Quoted By: >>55090700 >>55090981 >>55092162 >>55092409
>>55090480
I sort worldbuilding into three categories
1 - What I need to know so I can show it and not contradict myself
2 - What I should know but don't have to show, but does support item #1
3 - What I want to know, because it lets me define item #2

I tend to be very character-based, despite how many parts my stories and plots have. So my advice is usually to work in a cycle of characters -> world -> plot -> characters.
Your characters build the world, the world (and its conflicts) shape the big plot issues, and those trickle down to the more immediate plot conflicts that change characters.

Take it bit by bit and element by element. You'll get there if you don't get too wrapped up in making the first draft/idea perfect.

Anonymous Thu 16 Mar 2023 01:54:31 No.55090933 Report
Quoted By: >>55092021
>>55090718
A lot of practice.
Start with one-off stuff like greentext, maype just a few hundred words.
Read stories you like, but also ones that you might not like as much because they are challenging. Like drawing, you build up a toolkit as you are exposed to and then practice using techniques.

By starting with shorter stuff, you focus on learning to do more than a "a happened, then b happened" list of events. It will take time, but that practice will let you show as you tell (or show in layers, or imply, or etc...)

Four years on, and I started from 2k words. You've got to dare yourself and stop saying to yourself that you can't or you're not good enough.
